- "Revenue" if the corresponding B cell contains the word “deposit” (case‑insensitive)
- "Expenses" if it contains “withdrawal” (case‑insensitive)
- blank otherwise

We will write an `IF` formula using `LOWER` to make the check case‑insensitive. After writing the formulas, we will save the workbook to the output directory, run `recalculate()` to evaluate the formulas, reload the file with `data_only=True`, and print the resulting values in column E for rows 6‑13 to verify the change.
Code:
```repl
import os
import openpyxl
from openpyxl.utils import column_index_from_string

# Paths
input_path = input_spreadsheet  # provided variable
output_dir = "/sandbox/output/output_spreadsheet/"
os.makedirs(output_dir, exist_ok=True)
output_path = os.path.join(output_dir, os.path.basename(input_path))

# Load workbook (read/write)
wb = openpyxl.load_workbook(input_path)
ws = wb[wb.sheetnames[0]]  # assume first sheet

# Write formula to column E for all data rows (starting at row 6)
for r in range(6, ws.max_row + 1):
    # Build formula string (case‑insensitive)
    formula = f'=IF(LOWER(B{r})="deposit","Revenue",IF(LOWER(B{r})="withdrawal","Expenses",""))'
    ws.cell(row=r, column=column_index_from_string('E')).value = formula

# Save to output location
wb.save(output_path)

# Recalculate formulas (LibreOffice fallback)
calc_result = await recalculate(output_path)
print("Recalculate result:", calc_result)

# Reload with data_only to see evaluated values
wb_eval = openpyxl.load_workbook(output_path, data_only=True)
ws_eval = wb_eval[wb_eval.sheetnames[0]]

# Verify column E values for rows 6‑13
print("\nEvaluated values in column E (rows 6‑13):")
for r in range(6, 14):
    val = ws_eval.cell(row=r, column=column_index_from_string('E')).value
    print(f"E{r} =", val)
```
